selector_to_html = {"a[href=\"#overloading-template-functions\"]": "<h2 class=\"tippy-header\" style=\"margin-top: 0;\">Overloading Template Functions<a class=\"headerlink\" href=\"#overloading-template-functions\" title=\"Permalink to this heading\">#</a></h2><p>Several template functions may be created with the same identifier. For example we could have a function called myPrinter() that takes one argument in one version but takes two arguments in a second version.</p>", "a[href=\"#instantiation\"]": "<h2 class=\"tippy-header\" style=\"margin-top: 0;\">Instantiation<a class=\"headerlink\" href=\"#instantiation\" title=\"Permalink to this heading\">#</a></h2><p>When a program containing templates is compiled, a separate version of the template function is created for each concrete type required, which is called template instantiation; each of these are called non-template functions.</p>", "a[href=\"#practice\"]": "<h2 class=\"tippy-header\" style=\"margin-top: 0;\">Practice<a class=\"headerlink\" href=\"#practice\" title=\"Permalink to this heading\">#</a></h2><p>Practice Example 1.\nCreate a family of functions to compare two values, of char, int, float, and double types, and then return the larger value. Then replace the family of functions with a single template function.</p>", "a[href=\"#problems-using-templates\"]": "<h2 class=\"tippy-header\" style=\"margin-top: 0;\">Problems using templates<a class=\"headerlink\" href=\"#problems-using-templates\" title=\"Permalink to this heading\">#</a></h2><p>The great flexibility and more optimal performance afforded to the programmer by templates do come with some drawbacks. The biggest problem is the poor separation between the inner working of the template (the definition) and the interface (the declaration), which manifests itself in poor error diagnostics, with concomitantly unhelpful error message, that are often produced at a much later point in the compilation process than would be helpful.</p>", "a[href=\"#templates-functions-and-classes\"]": "<h1 class=\"tippy-header\" style=\"margin-top: 0;\">Templates Functions and Classes.<a class=\"headerlink\" href=\"#templates-functions-and-classes\" title=\"Permalink to this heading\">#</a></h1><p>Templates are used for generalisation and specialisation.</p><p>Templates are used to create generic functions and classes i.e. functions and classes were the return and argument, or parameter, types are not declared in their definitions - this allows the same code logic to be used with different data types.</p>", "a[href=\"#template-functions-with-several-parameters\"]": "<h2 class=\"tippy-header\" style=\"margin-top: 0;\">Template Functions with Several Parameters.<a class=\"headerlink\" href=\"#template-functions-with-several-parameters\" title=\"Permalink to this heading\">#</a></h2><p>A template function can have several template parameters.\nExample 3.</p>", "a[href=\"#class-templates\"]": "<h2 class=\"tippy-header\" style=\"margin-top: 0;\">Class Templates<a class=\"headerlink\" href=\"#class-templates\" title=\"Permalink to this heading\">#</a></h2><p>Copied from micosoft\nA class template can inherit all the constructors from a type argument if that type specifies a base class:</p>", "a[href=\"#advice-on-using-templates\"]": "<h2 class=\"tippy-header\" style=\"margin-top: 0;\">Advice on using Templates<a class=\"headerlink\" href=\"#advice-on-using-templates\" title=\"Permalink to this heading\">#</a></h2><p>Don\u2019t write a program with templates initially - start with a working version that has an overloaded function, i.e. one for each data type, and then replace the specified types with template parameters; this helps you avoid using some inbuild function that does not work, or behaves differently, for all the types you may consider.</p><p>Place all template definition in a header file.</p>"}
skip_classes = ["headerlink", "sd-stretched-link"]

window.onload = function () {
    for (const [select, tip_html] of Object.entries(selector_to_html)) {
        const links = document.querySelectorAll(` ${select}`);
        for (const link of links) {
            if (skip_classes.some(c => link.classList.contains(c))) {
                continue;
            }

            tippy(link, {
                content: tip_html,
                allowHTML: true,
                arrow: true,
                placement: 'auto-start', maxWidth: 500, interactive: false, theme: 'material', duration: [200, 100], delay: [200, 0],

            });
        };
    };
    console.log("tippy tips loaded!");
};
